	<div class="cell large-8 small-12 main-content-well">
		<div class="story-content">
							<div class="story-info">
			<div class="featured-img-container">
			<img class="story-img" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/Shadow-Ticket-726x400.jpg" title="October’s Best Reviewed Fiction">
					</div>
		<div class="story-heads">
		<h1>October’s Best Reviewed Fiction</h1>
		<h2>Featuring Thomas Pynchon, Gish Jen, Philip Pullman, and More</h2>	</div>
	</div>
										<div class="byline-date">
					<span class="byline"><a href="https://lithub.com/author/book-marks/"  title="Book Marks">Book Marks</a></span>
					<span class="hr"></span>
					<span class="date">October 31, 2025</span>
				</div>
						<div class="story-body">
								<p>Thomas Pynchon&#8217;s <em>Shadow Ticket</em>, Gish Jen&#8217;s <em>Bad Bad Girl</em>, and Philip Pullman&#8217;s <em>The Rose Field</em> all feature among the best reviewed books of the month.</p>
<p style="text-align: center;">Brought to you by <a href="https://bookmarks.reviews/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Book Marks</a>, Lit Hub’s home for book reviews.</p>
<p style="text-align: center;">*</p>
<p><img fetchpriority="high" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="134624" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/our-personalized-quarantine-book-recommendations/f7858995-0b7e-4bed-97ce-744ba8d1def7_1-059fcb5b9c8e3f8039b49f231fded12c/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/f7858995-0b7e-4bed-97ce-744ba8d1def7_1.059fcb5b9c8e3f8039b49f231fded12c.jpg" data-orig-size="1400,2176" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="John McPhee’s The Control of Nature" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/f7858995-0b7e-4bed-97ce-744ba8d1def7_1.059fcb5b9c8e3f8039b49f231fded12c-193x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/f7858995-0b7e-4bed-97ce-744ba8d1def7_1.059fcb5b9c8e3f8039b49f231fded12c-659x1024.jpg" class="size-medium wp-image-134624 aligncenter" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2025/09/The-Shadow-Ticket-197x300.jpeg" sizes="(max-width: 197px) 100vw, 197px" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2025/09/The-Shadow-Ticket-197x300.jpeg 197w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2025/09/The-Shadow-Ticket-33x50.jpeg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2025/09/The-Shadow-Ticket.jpeg 296w" alt="The Shadow Ticket" width="197" height="300" data-attachment-id="134624" data-permalink="https://bookmarks.reviews/5-reviews-you-need-to-read-this-week-9-25-2025/the-shadow-ticket/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2025/09/The-Shadow-Ticket.jpeg" data-orig-size="296,450" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="The Shadow Ticket" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2025/09/The-Shadow-Ticket-197x300.jpeg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2025/09/The-Shadow-Ticket.jpeg" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>1.<a href="https://bookmarks.reviews/reviews/shadow-ticket/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em> Shadow Ticket</em></a> by Thomas Pynchon<br />
(Penguin)</strong></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>13 Rave • 6 Positive • 6 Mixed • 4 Pan</strong></p>
<p>“It’s late Pynchon at his finest. Dark as a vampire’s pocket, light-fingered as a jewel thief, <em>Shadow Ticket</em> capers across the page with breezy, baggy-pants assurance—and then pauses on its way down the fire escape just long enough to crack your heart open … Pynchon may not have lost a step in <em>Shadow Ticket,</em> but sometimes he seems to be conserving his energy. His signature long, comma-rich sentences reach their periods a little sooner now … For most of the way, though, <em>Shadow Ticket</em> may remind you of an exceptionally tight tribute band, playing the oldies so lovingly that you might as well be listening to your old, long-since-unloaded vinyl.”</p>
<p style="text-align: right;">–David Kipen (<a href="https://www.latimes.com/entertainment-arts/books/story/2025-09-30/thomas-pynchon-new-book-shadow-ticket-review" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>The Los Angeles Times</em></a>)</p>
<p><img decoding="async" class="size-medium wp-image-134804 aligncenter" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2025/10/0cd377a6bc481736960f232aad020399-197x300.gif" sizes="(max-width: 197px) 100vw, 197px" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2025/10/0cd377a6bc481736960f232aad020399-197x300.gif 197w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2025/10/0cd377a6bc481736960f232aad020399-33x50.gif 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2025/10/0cd377a6bc481736960f232aad020399.gif 426w" alt="Bad Bad Girl Cover" width="197" height="300" data-attachment-id="134804" data-permalink="https://bookmarks.reviews/bookmark/bad-bad-girl/bad-bad-girl-cover/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2025/10/0cd377a6bc481736960f232aad020399.gif" data-orig-size="426,648" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Bad Bad Girl Cover" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2025/10/0cd377a6bc481736960f232aad020399-197x300.gif" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2025/10/0cd377a6bc481736960f232aad020399.gif" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>2. <a href="https://bookmarks.reviews/reviews/bad-bad-girl/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>Bad Bad Girl</em></a> by Gish Jen<br />
(Knopf)</strong></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>11 Rave • 2 Positive<br />
Read an essay by Gish Jen <a href="https://lithub.com/whats-real-and-whats-not-gish-jen-on-writing-between-the-factual-lines/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">here</a></strong></p>
<p>“Oscillates between plainspoken narrative and bold, italicized dialogues between Gish and her kvetching dead mother. The conceit is risky but pays off. The imagined colloquies punctuate the prose like counter melodies … The exchanges are edged with humor and skepticism: the mother scoffing at or replying brusquely to her daughter’s reminiscences, questions, speculations … What transforms it into a transcendent work of art is Jen’s empathy for all her characters.”</p>
<p style="text-align: right;">–Rhoda Feng (<a href="https://www.bostonglobe.com/2025/10/14/arts/gish-jen-bad-bad-girl-mother/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>The Boston Globe</em></a>)</p>
<p><a href="https://bookmarks.reviews/reviews/venetian-vespers/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><img decoding="async" class="wp-image-134723 size-medium aligncenter" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2025/10/e1c3a6a646e5e2351918b591019f8f52-199x300.gif" sizes="(max-width: 199px) 100vw, 199px" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2025/10/e1c3a6a646e5e2351918b591019f8f52-199x300.gif 199w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2025/10/e1c3a6a646e5e2351918b591019f8f52-33x50.gif 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2025/10/e1c3a6a646e5e2351918b591019f8f52.gif 429w" alt="Venetian Vespers Cover" width="199" height="300" data-attachment-id="134723" data-permalink="https://bookmarks.reviews/bookmark/venetian-vespers/venetian-vespers-cover/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2025/10/e1c3a6a646e5e2351918b591019f8f52.gif" data-orig-size="429,648" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Venetian Vespers Cover" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2025/10/e1c3a6a646e5e2351918b591019f8f52-199x300.gif" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2025/10/e1c3a6a646e5e2351918b591019f8f52.gif" /></a></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>3. <a href="https://bookmarks.reviews/reviews/venetian-vespers/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>Venetian Vespers</em></a> by John Banville</strong><br />
<strong>(Knopf)</strong></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>7 Rave • 4 Positive • 1 Mixed<br />
Read an excerpt from <em>Venetian Vespers</em> <a href="https://lithub.com/venetian-vespers/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">here</a></strong></p>
<p>“Maps out a territory halfway between Banville’s supreme fictions and his more forthright entertainments … An intricate thriller that is also a slyly fashioned work of art; a pastiche that is also indisputably the real thing. John Banville, up to his old tricks.”</p>
<p style="text-align: right;">–Kevin Power (<a href="https://www.irishtimes.com/culture/books/review/2025/09/29/venetian-vespers-by-john-banville-an-intricate-thriller-and-a-slyly-fashioned-work-of-art/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>The Irish Times</em></a>)</p>
<p><img decoding="async" class="size-medium wp-image-134766 aligncenter" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2025/10/e89b87f5f18ce1467225a03b431ed7c5-199x300.gif" sizes="auto, (max-width: 199px) 100vw, 199px" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2025/10/e89b87f5f18ce1467225a03b431ed7c5-199x300.gif 199w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2025/10/e89b87f5f18ce1467225a03b431ed7c5-33x50.gif 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2025/10/e89b87f5f18ce1467225a03b431ed7c5.gif 429w" alt="Big Kiss, Bye-Bye Cover" width="199" height="300" data-attachment-id="134766" data-permalink="https://bookmarks.reviews/bookmark/big-kiss-bye-bye/big-kiss-bye-bye-cover/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2025/10/e89b87f5f18ce1467225a03b431ed7c5.gif" data-orig-size="429,648" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Big Kiss, Bye-Bye Cover" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2025/10/e89b87f5f18ce1467225a03b431ed7c5-199x300.gif" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2025/10/e89b87f5f18ce1467225a03b431ed7c5.gif" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>4. <a href="https://bookmarks.reviews/reviews/big-kiss-bye-bye/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>Big Kiss, Bye-Bye</em></a> by Claire-Louise Bennett</strong><br />
<strong>(Riverhead)</strong></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>6 Rave • 5 Positive • 3 Mixed</strong></p>
<p>“Themes of relationships and communication might seem at odds with Bennett’s quest to shuck off the self and write from somewhere deeper, but therein lies the magic of <em>Big Kiss, Bye-Bye</em> … Fertile new ground for the author, and her prose is ideally suited to exploring them. Shape-shifting and splendid in its disregard for conventional wisdom and contemporary minimalist tastes, it weaves rococo abundance and brazen mundanity into something as porous and unknowable as the narrator’s inner world. Claire-Louise Bennett is a true original, working at the brink of what language can do.”</p>
<p style="text-align: right;">–Annie McDermott (<a href="https://www.the-tls.com/literature/fiction/big-kiss-bye-bye-claire-louise-bennett-book-review-annie-mcdermott" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Times Literary Supplement</em></a>)</p>
<p><a href="https://bookmarks.reviews/reviews/the-rose-field/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><img decoding="async" class="wp-image-134896 size-medium aligncenter" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2025/10/b5f5fa7f64cf592cc6f77780019c0c08-211x300.gif" sizes="auto, (max-width: 211px) 100vw, 211px" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2025/10/b5f5fa7f64cf592cc6f77780019c0c08-211x300.gif 211w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2025/10/b5f5fa7f64cf592cc6f77780019c0c08-35x50.gif 35w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2025/10/b5f5fa7f64cf592cc6f77780019c0c08.gif 455w" alt="The Book of Dust: The Rose Field (Book of Dust, Volume 3) Cover" width="211" height="300" data-attachment-id="134896" data-permalink="https://bookmarks.reviews/bookmark/the-rose-field/the-book-of-dust-the-rose-field-book-of-dust-volume-3-cover/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2025/10/b5f5fa7f64cf592cc6f77780019c0c08.gif" data-orig-size="455,648" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="The Book of Dust: The Rose Field (Book of Dust, Volume 3) Cover" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2025/10/b5f5fa7f64cf592cc6f77780019c0c08-211x300.gif" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2025/10/b5f5fa7f64cf592cc6f77780019c0c08.gif" /></a></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>5. <a href="https://bookmarks.reviews/reviews/the-rose-field/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>The Rose Field (Book of Dust, Volume 3)</em></a> by Philip Pullman</strong><br />
<strong>(Knopf)</strong></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>5 Rave • 4 Positive • 2 Mixed</strong></p>
<p>“Jam-packed with chases, daring escapes, splendidly operatic scene setting (including an evil sorcerer’s titanic mountain forge), strange and magnificent creatures, and charismatic supporting characters that readers will clutch to their hearts with undying love. It is tremendously entertaining … Questions may niggle at some readers, but they don’t interfere much with the pleasures dispensed by <em>The Rose Field</em>, from its thrilling action sequences to the return of such indelible creations as the witches with their harsh, ascetic wisdom and ragged elegance. The novel’s moments of keen emotion resonate especially well because Pullman never stoops to sentimentality or can’t.”</p>
<p style="text-align: right;">–Laura Miller (<a href="https://slate.com/culture/2025/10/philip-pullman-book-of-dust-the-rose-field-his-dark-materials-lyra.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Slate</em></a>)</p>
